But no one ranks above Ryan. No one has done more, achieved more or represented the club more impressively, on and off the field. He's the best signing Stoke have made in my lifetime, and I'll always be thankful that he spent 14 years with my club. Thanks, Ryan @kathbuckley (7/7)

Football fans fall in love with players easily and I can think of so many who I've adored for different reasons, from skilful thrillers like Hoekstra, Fuller and Bojan, to tenacious warriors like Taggart, Huth and Walters. There are dozens more who I've loved watching. (6/7)

In 2008, Stoke had endured 23 years out of the top flight and were a middling Championship club playing in front of half-full stadiums. Apathy was the dominant emotion on many a match day. Ryan didn't single handedly change that, of course, but no player did more. (5/7)

- Promotion
- 10 PL seasons (nine more than almost anyone expected)
- A first FA Cup final (and that staggering 5-0 at Wembley)
- European football (I even watched Stoke at the Mestalla, ffs!!!) 
- Signings, performances and results we could only previously have dreamed of

(4/7) https://t.co/aGCiq2dzmq

Even with all the optimism that surrounded the news, no one could have imagined what Stoke and Ryan would go on to achieve over the next decade.

As the club enjoyed its best times since the 1970s, our number 17 was at the heart of it all, continually setting the standard. (3/7)

Stoke simply hadn't made this sort of signing for so long, which meant converting Ryan's loan to a permanent deal was massive.

Suddenly promotion to the top flight for the first time in more than two decades seemed realistic. We were really going for it. (2/7)

I've rarely been more excited by a signing than when we signed Ryan permanently in 2008.

It felt like such a statement of intent. For years we'd predominantly signed journeymen or loanees (or both) on the cheap. Now it was seven figures on a 20-y-o with HUGE potential. (1/7) https://t.co/VnP8UXKFLq

My message, for what it's worth, is this:

If you are LGBT+ and don't feel able to come out right now, just know that things can change and you can be happy - not just happy, but so much happier than ever before - living as your authentic self. 

#NationalComingOutDay

Happily, with the support of a few special people, I was able to come out later in 2011. 

I've gradually become more comfortable with who I am and yesterday I had the amazing opportunity to co-present a workshop at the #PrideSportsSummit (thanks @jonboy79 & @LouEnglefield!) 2/3 https://t.co/BjnsG4sdsT

Coming out is different for everyone, but for a lot of LGBT+ people, it can feel impossible.

Eight years ago, I knew I was gay but I couldn't see how I could tell people. I was scared, lonely and my behaviour was erratic and irresponsible as a result.

#NationalComingOutDay 1/3

Given how long it took me to come out, it felt pretty cool today when an email was sent to all Perform staff launching the network I proposed, and listing me as the point of contact for any initial questions. Can't wait to see how the network develops.

For a long time, in my teens and early twenties, I felt being open about my sexuality would make it impossible, or at least difficult, to work in sports media.

Happily, I've been surrounded by people at PA and Perform who have ensured it has not been a barrier at all.

Around 3 months ago, inspired by @jonboy79 and @SportsMediaLGBT, I proposed the creation of an LGBT+ network at @perform. 

Today, thanks to the enthusiastic buy-in of numerous colleagues, that network was officially launched. 

I am excited and proud in equal measure.
